docs.abstract: A new racial justice commission will make policy recommendations that could include baby bonds, a jobs guarantee or reparations for Black residents.
docs.snippet: A new racial justice commission will make policy recommendations that could include baby bonds, a jobs guarantee or reparations for Black residents.
docs.lead_paragraph: After a year where the pandemic and protests over police brutality underscored New York City’s broad racial inequities, Mayor Bill de Blasio has unveiled a sweeping initiative to examine and remake the City Charter to correct imbalances.

headline.main: After Unrest and Protests, N.Y.C. Creates Group to Dismantle Structural Racism
headline.print_headline: New York City Creates Commission to Fight Structural Racism

docs.abstract: Two seats for the trial of Derek Chauvin are reserved for journalists. Outside the courtroom, many other members of the media are standing by.
docs.snippet: Two seats for the trial of Derek Chauvin are reserved for journalists. Outside the courtroom, many other members of the media are standing by.
docs.lead_paragraph: Because of the pandemic, a limited audience has been allowed to watch the trial of Derek Chauvin from inside the courtroom. Among those allowed inside are the judge, the jurors, the witnesses, the court staff, the lawyers and Mr. Chauvin himself. One seat has been set aside for a member of George Floyd’s family and one for Mr. Chauvin’s.

headline.main: Inside the courtroom, a rotating pool of journalists is monitoring the developments.

docs.abstract: Inquiries into law enforcement’s handling of the George Floyd protests last summer found insufficient training and militarized responses — a widespread failure in policing nationwide.
docs.snippet: Inquiries into law enforcement’s handling of the George Floyd protests last summer found insufficient training and militarized responses — a widespread failure in policing nationwide.
docs.lead_paragraph: For many long weeks last summer, protesters in American cities faced off against their own police forces in what proved to be, for major law enforcement agencies across the country, a startling display of violence and disarray.

headline.main: In City After City, Police Mishandled Black Lives Matter Protests
headline.print_headline: Reports Hammer Police Responses To 2020 Protests

byline.original: By Kim Barker, Mike Baker and Ali Watkins

docs.abstract: The city had faced criticism over plans to pay social media influencers $2,000 each to fight misinformation during the trials of Derek Chauvin and three other former police officers charged in George Floyd’s death.
docs.snippet: The city had faced criticism over plans to pay social media influencers $2,000 each to fight misinformation during the trials of Derek Chauvin and three other former police officers charged in George Floyd’s death.
docs.lead_paragraph: The City of Minneapolis has abandoned a contentious plan to pay social media influencers $2,000 each to help it combat misinformation during the upcoming trials of four police officers charged in the killing of George Floyd, officials said on Monday.

headline.main: Minneapolis Abandons Plan to Pay Influencers During Officers’ Trials

docs.abstract: Before prosecutors called their first witness, lawyers for both sides made opening statements to jurors in the trial of Derek Chauvin, the former Minneapolis police officer charged with murder in George Floyd’s death.
docs.snippet: Before prosecutors called their first witness, lawyers for both sides made opening statements to jurors in the trial of Derek Chauvin, the former Minneapolis police officer charged with murder in George Floyd’s death.
docs.lead_paragraph: Before prosecutors called their first witness, lawyers for both sides made opening statements to jurors in the trial of Derek Chauvin, the former Minneapolis police officer charged with murder in George Floyd’s death. Here’s what happened.

headline.main: What we learned from the opening statements.

docs.abstract: “My instincts were telling me that something’s wrong,” Jena Scurry testified in court on Monday.
docs.snippet: “My instincts were telling me that something’s wrong,” Jena Scurry testified in court on Monday.
docs.lead_paragraph: A 911 dispatcher who watched the police pin George Floyd to the ground on a surveillance camera said in court on Monday that the restraint went on for so long that she asked someone if her “screens had frozen.”

headline.main: A 911 dispatcher said officers pinned down George Floyd for so long she thought the camera feed ‘had frozen.’

headline.main: In the Presence of George Floyd

docs.abstract: The 12-member jury includes two white men, four white women, three Black men, one Black women and two women who identify as mixed race, according to information provided by the court.
docs.snippet: The 12-member jury includes two white men, four white women, three Black men, one Black women and two women who identify as mixed race, according to information provided by the court.
docs.lead_paragraph: The jury for the murder trial of Derek Chauvin in the death of George Floyd has been seated, clearing the way for the opening arguments in the trial, set to begin on Monday.

headline.main: The jury in the murder trial of Derek Chauvin has been seated.

docs.abstract: The first three jurors were selected on Tuesday, with one saying he was not “scared to take on a trial of this magnitude.”
docs.snippet: The first three jurors were selected on Tuesday, with one saying he was not “scared to take on a trial of this magnitude.”
docs.lead_paragraph: The first three jurors were selected on Tuesday for the trial of Derek Chauvin, the former Minneapolis police officer accused of second-degree murder in the death of George Floyd.

headline.main: What happened on the first day of jury selection at the Derek Chauvin trial?

docs.abstract: News that the City of Minneapolis had agreed to pay $27 million to the family of George Floyd made it hard for them to be impartial about the former police officer accused of killing him, the jurors said.
docs.snippet: News that the City of Minneapolis had agreed to pay $27 million to the family of George Floyd made it hard for them to be impartial about the former police officer accused of killing him, the jurors said.
